40|$|Nijim,Monther:The paper {{considers}} {{circular migration}} {{with regard to}} Palestinian migrant workers and alien workers in Palestine, {{in the context of}} the EU Commission Communication on Circular Migration (2007). Throughout the paper, the unusualness of <b>the</b> <b>Palestinian</b> situation, both with regards to border control and the lack of sovereignty of <b>the</b> <b>Palestinian</b> <b>Authorities</b> is underlined. <b>The</b> paper looks in depth at the movement between Palestine and Israel as well as border crossings with the rest of the world. Owing to its sovereignty deficit, <b>the</b> <b>Palestinian</b> <b>Authorities</b> have not legislated directly on migration, but some legal norms do have an indirect impact. Further, the paper reviews legal obstacles to leaving the country and the question of dual nationality is also addressed and, the issuing of work permits by <b>the</b> <b>Palestinian</b> <b>Authorities</b> to non-Palestinian workers is explained. Finally, <b>the</b> role that <b>Palestinian</b> delegations should play with regard to their workers abroad is considere...|$|R
5|$|Jamal {{was taken}} {{at first to}} the Al-Shifa Hospital in Gaza. Dr. Ahmed Ghadeel said Jamal had {{received}} multiple wounds from high-velocity bullets striking his right elbow, right thigh and {{the lower part of}} both legs; his femoral artery was also cut. Talal Abu Rahma interviewed Jamal and the doctor there on camera the day after the shooting; Dr. Ghadeel displayed x-rays of Jamal's right elbow and right pelvis. Moshe Tamam, Jamal's Israeli employer, offered to have him taken to hospital in Tel Aviv, but <b>the</b> <b>Palestinian</b> <b>Authority</b> declined the offer. He was transferred instead to the King Hussein Medical Center in Amman, Jordan, where he was visited by King Abdullah. Jamal reportedly told Tamam that he had been hit by nine bullets; he said five were removed from his body in hospital in Gaza and four in Amman.|$|E
